  "footnotes": [
    "Margiana (Merv / Mary): one of the greatest oasis cities of the ancient and medieval world; the BMAC flourished here c.2300–1700 BCE; under the Achaemenids it was the Margiana satrapy; Merv became a major Silk Road hub and, under the Seljuk Sultan Sanjar, briefly the capital of the Great Seljuk Empire (early 12th century); the Mongol destruction of 1221 was catastrophic but the city was later rebuilt",
    "Parthia / Nisa: the original heartland of the Arsacid Parthians, who rose from the Parni/Dahae nomadic confederation near the Caspian; Nisa (near modern Ashgabat) served as the Arsacid dynastic capital and royal necropolis; the Parthian Empire (247 BCE–224 CE) was the dominant power between Rome and China for four centuries",
    "Seljuk Empire at Merv: the Great Seljuk sultan Ahmad Sanjar (r.1118–1157) made Merv his permanent residence and the imperial capital; under his patronage Merv was arguably the largest city in the world; his defeat by the Qara Khitai (1141) marked the beginning of Seljuk decline",
    "Russian conquest: Gen. Mikhail Skobelev destroyed the Tekke Turkmen fortress at Geok-Tepe (January 1881), opening the path to Ashgabat; Russia annexed Merv in 1884 without battle, completing the conquest of Turkmenistan; the railway from Krasnovodsk was the key instrument of control",
    "Transcaspian Provisional Government (1918–1919): a Social-Revolutionary and White-aligned government based in Ashgabat that briefly controlled most of Turkmenistan with British support from Meshed (Iran); overthrown by the Red Army; one of the many forgotten fronts of the Russian Civil War",
    "Turkmen SSR (1924–1991): created by Soviet national delimitation; Turkmens had no prior unified statehood — the new republic aggregated Tekke, Yomut, Ersari, and other tribal territories; declared independence in October 1991 under Saparmurat Niyazov (Turkmenbashi)"
  ]
